{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "In Chinese, on the surface, the comparative form of a gradable adjective is identical to its plain form (Grano 2012), as shown in (3).",
    "There is no morphological marking when making comparisons in Chinese.",
    "By contrast, for many other languages in the world, the comparative form is derived from the positive form (Grano and Davis 2018).",
    "For example, in English, a comparative morpheme -er or a word such as more is needed to mark comparison.",
    "As illustrated in Grano and Davis (2018), in Irish, affix -a marks comparison as in arda \"taller,\" and in French, a word plus marks comparison as in plus grand \"taller.\""
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "In Chinese, on the surface, the comparative form of a gradable adjective is identical to its plain form (Grano 2012), as shown in (3).",
    "By contrast, for many other languages in the world, the comparative form is derived from the positive form (Grano and Davis 2018).",
    "As illustrated in Grano and Davis (2018), in Irish, affix -a marks comparison as in arda \"taller,\" and in French, a word plus marks comparison as in plus grand \"taller.\""
